when I got here.

33:32.178 --> 33:34.379
I even bought a bow tie.

33:36.582 --> 33:39.351
No, we're never going to be friends.

33:39.385 --> 33:42.788
But I respect you as a doctor.

33:42.822 --> 33:44.589
And I think you respect me, too,

33:44.624 --> 33:45.924
and if you want to know
the truth--

33:45.959 --> 33:48.026
William: I don't.

33:48.061 --> 33:49.628
Respect you.

33:49.662 --> 33:52.464
Not in the least.

33:55.167 --> 33:57.569
Ethan: Maybe it's the fact
that I'm with Virginia now, huh?

33:59.171 --> 34:00.838
And that's what this
is really about, isn't it?

34:00.873 --> 34:03.174
William: Clear the room.
All of you, out-- now.

34:08.981 --> 34:11.715
She didn't have to tell me,
you know.

34:11.750 --> 34:13.449
It was obvious.

34:13.485 --> 34:15.052
Ethan: Who, Virginia?

34:15.087 --> 34:16.853
William:
16 years of medical experience.

34:16.889 --> 34:18.656
You think I believe in miracles?

34:18.690 --> 34:21.958
Did you think I wouldn't know,

34:21.994 --> 34:24.226
with her sleeping right there
beside me?

34:24.262 --> 34:26.697
You're lucky I don't come after
your medical license.

34:26.731 --> 34:28.799
Ethan: I have no idea
what you're talking--

34:28.833 --> 34:30.167
Unh!

34:32.069 --> 34:34.705
William: I'm talking
about my pregnant wife!

34:39.678 --> 34:43.213
Ethan: Libby's pregnant?

34:43.246 --> 34:45.849
Jesus.

34:45.882 --> 34:47.918
William:
I know what you did.

34:47.952 --> 34:49.385
You're finished
at this hospital.

34:49.420 --> 34:53.023
Ethan: Any normal man would be
shaking my hand right now.

34:53.056 --> 34:54.757
I mean, you may not like the way
it happened--

34:54.792 --> 34:57.360
William: You stepped into something
you can't even begin to understand,

34:57.394 --> 34:59.329
like a child--

34:59.363 --> 35:04.133
willful and stupid, completely
unaware of what you've done!

35:04.167 --> 35:08.438
Ethan: I capped Libby because you
were too selfish to do it yourself.

35:08.472 --> 35:10.005
I like your wife.

35:10.040 --> 35:12.642
She deserves to be a mother.

35:14.110 --> 35:15.311
And you know what?

35:15.345 --> 35:18.814
Even though it cost me my job,
I'd do it again.

35:21.784 --> 35:25.154
[ Door opens, closes ]

35:25.188 --> 35:27.022
William: Ah.

37:25.537 --> 37:27.105
[ Feedback ]

37:27.139 --> 37:28.606
Woman on PA:
<i>Back to the triage drill,</i>

37:28.640 --> 37:31.676
<i>will commence in 30 minutes.</i>
[ Elevator bell dings ]

37:31.710 --> 37:33.945
[ Indistinct conversations ]

37:35.948 --> 37:37.882
Fitzhugh: [ Clears throat ]

37:39.085 --> 37:41.119
Lillian: Oh.

37:41.153 --> 37:42.653
Chancellor Fitzhugh.

37:42.688 --> 37:43.888
Dr. Lillian DePaul,

37:43.922 --> 37:46.691
one of your happy minions
on the fourth floor.

37:49.628 --> 37:53.898
What a delightful necktie.
What would you call that color?

37:55.233 --> 37:57.602
Fitzhugh: Red.

38:02.640 --> 38:04.875
Lillian: You look like
a man who enjoys the links.

38:04.909 --> 38:06.543
Are you a member
at Norwood Hills?

38:06.577 --> 38:08.745
Fitzhugh:
Hmm. For 20-odd years.

38:08.779 --> 38:10.347
Although I never find the time.

38:10.382 --> 38:12.483
Of course,
they find the time to bill you.

38:12.517 --> 38:14.118
Lillian: [ Chuckles ]

38:14.152 --> 38:17.654
Fitzhugh: My wife's
on the membership committee.

38:17.688 --> 38:19.322
Lillian:
What's your wife's handicap?

38:21.024 --> 38:23.392
Fitzhugh:
Estelle had polio as a girl,

38:23.426 --> 38:27.095
but with her cane, she gets
around just as well as you or I.

38:31.835 --> 38:33.802
Lillian: Well,
speaking of women's health,

38:33.837 --> 38:35.604
I have a program
in cancer detection,

38:35.639 --> 38:40.108
which could use the support of
a man with your unique vision.

38:40.143 --> 38:41.510
Fitzhugh: What form?

38:41.544 --> 38:42.977
Lillian:
Well, a check, ideally.

38:43.012 --> 38:44.846
Fitzhugh:
What form of cancer?

38:44.880 --> 38:46.748
Lillian: Oh. Cervical.

38:46.782 --> 38:49.051
Fitzhugh: Mm.

38:49.085 --> 38:52.087
I suppose if a woman
were going to dabble in cancer,

38:52.121 --> 38:54.255
that would be
the natural choice.

38:54.289 --> 38:56.024
- Or uterine.
- Lillian: Or breast.

38:56.058 --> 38:58.359
We have two of those.

38:58.393 --> 39:01.195
[ Elevator bell dings ]

39:01.229 --> 39:02.797
[ Indistinct conversations ]

39:02.831 --> 39:05.700
I'd welcome the opportunity
to walk you through my proposal.

39:05.734 --> 39:07.869
Fitzhugh: My secretary
can arrange an appointment.

39:07.903 --> 39:10.471
Lillian: I spoke to her. Your
next opening is in three weeks.

39:10.505 --> 39:12.973
But I thought, if you were free
for a drink this evening...

39:13.007 --> 39:14.641
- Fitzhugh: Dr. DePaul--
- Lillian: Lillian.

39:14.676 --> 39:18.645
Fitzhugh: Dr. DePaul, I
don't know what kind of notions

39:18.680 --> 39:20.647
you've picked up
on the fourth floor,

39:20.682 --> 39:23.417
but I am a happily married man.

39:33.595 --> 39:36.063
William:
My office-- now.

39:43.370 --> 39:45.105
Shut the door.

39:53.714 --> 39:55.681
Perhaps I didn't make myself
clearer this morning--

39:55.716 --> 39:57.650
you are not to bother
Dr. Langham

39:57.684 --> 39:59.185
about this pregnancy matter.

39:59.220 --> 40:01.253
Virginia:
"Pregnancy matter"?

40:01.287 --> 40:03.723
Do you have any idea
what it takes

40:03.757 --> 40:06.125
to raise a child
as a single mother?

40:06.159 --> 40:08.594
William: We don't know the first
thing about that woman, Virginia.

40:08.629 --> 40:09.829
Virginia: We know plenty.

40:09.863 --> 40:12.498
We know the diameter
of her areolae.

40:12.532 --> 40:14.700
We know her heart rate
during climax,

40:14.735 --> 40:17.035
how quickly she moves
into the plateau phase,

40:17.069 --> 40:19.104
- systolic pressure--
- William: Exactly.

40:19.139 --> 40:21.306
Our subjects stand naked
in our exam rooms.

40:21.341 --> 40:22.774
They copulate with strangers.

40:22.808 --> 40:25.110
What we offer in return
is a simple promise--

40:25.145 --> 40:28.447
a promise to honor their
privacy-- a promise you broke.

40:28.481 --> 40:30.582
Virginia: I did not break
Langham's anonymity.

40:30.617 --> 40:31.617
I gave him a choice.

40:31.651 --> 40:34.352
William:
No, you trapped him, Virginia.

40:34.386 --> 40:36.121
He no longer has a choice,

40:36.155 --> 40:39.257
because he can never unknow
what you told him.

40:39.291 --> 40:41.993
You did this all on your own,
against my wishes.

40:42.028 --> 40:44.929
Honest to God, Virginia,
who do you think you are?!

40:46.032 --> 40:50.434
[ Air-raid siren blaring ]

40:50.469 --> 40:52.570
[ Footsteps depart ]

40:52.604 --> 40:56.974
[ Door opens, closes ]

40:57.008 --> 40:58.676
[ Indistinct talking ]

40:58.710 --> 41:00.344
Jane:
Everyone take your positions!

41:00.379 --> 41:04.582
We have 1,400 casualties
on the way!

41:09.520 --> 41:11.655
Virginia: Ethan?

41:14.592 --> 41:16.760
That's stage blood, isn't it?

41:16.795 --> 41:19.296
Ethan: Unfortunately, no.
Your boss sucker-punched me.

41:19.330 --> 41:22.332
Virginia: Bill hit you?

41:22.366 --> 41:24.701
Ethan: Thanks, Roberta.
Would you...

41:28.206 --> 41:29.372
I guess I deserve it

41:29.407 --> 41:31.040
for giving the guy
the best gift of his life.

41:31.075 --> 41:32.975
Virginia:
Ethan, what is going on?

41:33.010 --> 41:35.111
Ethan:
Uh, it has to do with Libby,

41:35.145 --> 41:37.514
her blank-shooting
jackass of a husband,

41:37.548 --> 41:41.184
and how she really got pregnant.

41:42.385 --> 41:45.088
[ Blaring continues ]

41:58.968 --> 42:00.869
Man: [ Grunting ]

42:17.553 --> 42:19.121
[ Baby cries ]

42:56.992 --> 42:58.926
Margaret:
[ Breathing deeply ]

43:01.562 --> 43:04.598
Austin: Well, California's
been wiped off the map.

43:04.632 --> 43:07.668
They're announcing death tolls
on the radio

43:07.702 --> 43:10.103
like they're baseball scores.

43:10.137 --> 43:13.740
Margaret: [ Sighs ]
What are you doing here?

43:13.775 --> 43:18.178
Austin: I remembered
you like to swim at night.

43:18.212 --> 43:21.247
I had to get out
of the hospital.

43:21.282 --> 43:24.250
Couldn't bring myself
to go home.

43:26.253 --> 43:30.623
All anyone wants to talk about
is the end of the world.

43:32.993 --> 43:36.261
Margaret: [ Sighs ]
It feels like it <i>is</i> the end.

43:43.470 --> 43:48.541
Austin: Look, I know we didn't...
leave things on the best terms.

43:48.575 --> 43:53.578
So, if, um...
you want me to buzz off...

44:00.053 --> 44:02.988
Margaret: Did you bring
your bathing suit?

44:24.910 --> 44:27.511
Virginia:
Thank you for meeting me.

44:27.545 --> 44:30.147
It's-- it's been quite a day.

44:30.182 --> 44:33.717
Flora:
Did the doc tell you to call me?

44:33.752 --> 44:35.486
Clean up the mess?

44:35.520 --> 44:39.656
Virginia: Well, that would take
a pretty big mop.

44:43.961 --> 44:48.699
Flora: I'm not fishing for a
husband, if that's what you think.

44:48.733 --> 44:51.568
I didn't even like that guy.

44:51.603 --> 44:53.904
But this kid is half his,

44:53.938 --> 44:57.040
and I thought
maybe I could get to know him.

45:06.350 --> 45:08.851
Thank you.

45:08.886 --> 45:11.888
Virginia: I'm sorry. I can't give
you his name or his information.

45:13.757 --> 45:16.292
Flora:
Then what is this?

45:16.326 --> 45:19.929
Virginia: Not enough.

45:19.963 --> 45:25.968
It never is.
Trust me, I have two.

45:26.002 --> 45:28.070
But it's better than nothing.

45:28.104 --> 45:31.140
Flora: This is from you?

45:32.542 --> 45:34.509
Virginia: No, it's...

45:34.544 --> 45:37.346
from the man who's responsible.

45:57.533 --> 46:00.168
Jane:
I hope I didn't ruin your shot.

46:00.202 --> 46:04.272
Lester: Oh, uh...
I can cut around you.

46:04.306 --> 46:08.409
Though I-I'm no great fan
of montage.

46:08.444 --> 46:11.946
I don't suppose
you've read André Bazin,

46:11.981 --> 46:14.082
"The Ontology
Of The Photographic Image"?

46:14.116 --> 46:16.250
Jane:
I'm waiting for the movie.

46:16.285 --> 46:18.453
Lester:
It's pretty theoretical.

46:18.487 --> 46:20.754
Pseudorealism
versus true realism.

46:20.789 --> 46:22.490
Jane:
What's the difference?

46:22.524 --> 46:25.626
Lester:
Honestly, I have no idea.

46:28.062 --> 46:29.363
Jane: You know,

46:29.397 --> 46:32.466
the film you're shooting
won't survive a nuclear attack.

46:32.501 --> 46:34.334
Nothing will.

46:34.369 --> 46:36.636
Except cockroaches.

46:36.670 --> 46:39.339
Lester: And Godzilla.

46:39.374 --> 46:42.075
Jane: They don't tell you this
in civil defense class--

46:42.110 --> 46:44.611
but I've been reading this book,
"On The Beach"--

46:44.645 --> 46:47.614
and the H-bomb has
a blast radius 10 miles wide.

46:49.017 --> 46:52.552
If one falls on St. Louis,
they won't even find our teeth.

46:52.586 --> 46:54.186
We'll just be numbers

46:54.221 --> 46:58.591
in an official death toll
added up in some city far away.

46:58.626 --> 47:00.426
Lester: Heavy.

47:00.460 --> 47:02.395
Jane:
At the end of the day,

47:02.429 --> 47:05.364
if you're facing
global annihilation,

47:05.399 --> 47:09.435
you can only be accountable
for yourself.

47:09.469 --> 47:11.037
If it were the last night
on Earth,

47:11.071 --> 47:13.305
I'd feel really bad about
what I said to you earlier.

47:14.707 --> 47:16.975
So...

47:17.010 --> 47:19.545
I'm sorry.

47:19.579 --> 47:25.851
Lester: And if-- if it
were the last night on Earth...

47:25.885 --> 47:28.119
I'd kiss you.

47:51.310 --> 47:54.512
Virginia:
I need to speak with you, Bill.

47:54.547 --> 47:56.881
William: Well, it'll
have to wait until tomorrow.

47:56.915 --> 47:59.516
It's past dinner hour.
Libby will be expecting me home.

47:59.551 --> 48:01.652
Virginia: Is she?

48:01.687 --> 48:03.287
Expecting?

48:06.925 --> 48:09.293
I do hope
you'll congratulate her for me.

48:11.162 --> 48:14.799
After everything she's been
through, it is wonderful news--

48:14.833 --> 48:16.266
Libby's pregnancy.

48:20.505 --> 48:23.339
William: [ Sighs ]

48:23.373 --> 48:24.440
Virginia...

48:24.475 --> 48:28.744
Virginia:
Bill, I never felt smaller

48:28.778 --> 48:30.713
than I did
the day that you offered to pay

48:30.747 --> 48:32.715
for my participation
in our study.

48:34.651 --> 48:36.486
I spent weeks

48:36.520 --> 48:40.990
trying to figure out why
you would treat me that way...

48:41.024 --> 48:46.461
like I was just
some random volunteer, or worse,

48:46.496 --> 48:49.264
but... now I understand.

48:49.298 --> 48:51.967
William: [ Clears throat ]
I'm sure you can imagine

48:52.002 --> 48:54.802
Libby's reluctance
to talk about the baby.

48:54.837 --> 48:58.640
Virginia: That's not why
you didn't tell me.

48:58.674 --> 49:02.611
It's because you felt guilty...

49:02.645 --> 49:07.982
Because you had formed
an attachment to me.

49:12.254 --> 49:14.221
William: It's been a trying day.
You're emotional.

49:14.256 --> 49:16.057
Virginia: No, Bill.

49:16.091 --> 49:19.360
<i>You</i> are.

49:19.394 --> 49:20.895
You do always say

49:20.929 --> 49:22.930
that we that can't let emotions
cloud our judgment,

49:22.965 --> 49:26.067
but you did.

49:28.570 --> 49:34.175
Which means it was...
never really about the research.

49:35.310 --> 49:39.046
No. We were having an affair.

49:39.080 --> 49:41.282
William: [ Scoffs lightly ]

49:43.552 --> 49:44.951
Are you finished?

49:44.986 --> 49:47.520
Virginia: No. Not quite.

49:50.524 --> 49:52.592
I met with Flora Banks tonight.

49:53.861 --> 49:58.431
Subject F-26-132.

49:58.465 --> 50:02.402
And I gave her a check
for $2,000

50:02.436 --> 50:04.637
from the discretionary fund.

50:04.672 --> 50:06.105
William: You did what?

50:06.139 --> 50:07.373
Virginia:
You obviously think

50:07.408 --> 50:09.542
that money is the best way
to handle the problem.

50:09.577 --> 50:11.311
William:
That is a gross violation--

50:11.345 --> 50:14.247
Virginia: I have the legal
authority. You granted it to me.

50:16.183 --> 50:18.517
Although it still is
a fireable offense.

50:18.551 --> 50:20.252
But...

50:20.286 --> 50:23.555
don't worry, Bill.

50:23.590 --> 50:25.791
I quit.

50:46.078 --> 50:48.046
Austin:
I got some lousy news today.

50:48.080 --> 50:49.914
Margaret: So did I.

50:49.949 --> 50:53.317
Austin: Trust me,
I think I got you beat.

50:55.121 --> 50:58.857
'Course, if they drop the bomb,
none of it matters anyway.

51:01.761 --> 51:04.395
Hmm.

51:11.002 --> 51:15.005
You know we're building
artificial satellites?

51:15.039 --> 51:19.744
Shoot 'em into space,
and they just... float around.

51:19.778 --> 51:22.212
No tether.

51:22.247 --> 51:25.082
No responsibilities.

51:25.116 --> 51:28.385
That's how I used to feel.

51:29.453 --> 51:32.589
Margaret:
They're not actually floating.

51:32.623 --> 51:34.024
Austin: Hmm?

51:34.058 --> 51:35.993
Margaret: My daughter
took a science class.

51:36.027 --> 51:38.461
I borrowed her book.

51:38.496 --> 51:42.165
There are thousands of objects
in orbit.

51:43.901 --> 51:49.406
Gravity pulls them toward Earth,
but the Earth keeps...

51:49.440 --> 51:53.576
curving away underneath them.

51:53.611 --> 51:56.913
They're not actually floating.

51:56.947 --> 51:59.481
What they're really doing...

52:01.084 --> 52:04.921
is falling.

52:14.531 --> 52:17.533
[ Typewriter keys
clacking slowly ]

52:34.683 --> 52:37.752
Virginia: I see
you still need a secretary.

52:40.022 --> 52:42.190
You look nice.

52:44.660 --> 52:47.628
Lillian:
I look like a rodeo clown.

52:47.663 --> 52:49.697
Though a clown
would have had more success

52:49.732 --> 52:51.833
charming the Chancellor.

52:55.437 --> 53:01.275
Virginia: The Chancellor works
for the trustees, doesn't he?

53:02.543 --> 53:04.444
Lillian:
Technically, I suppose.

53:04.479 --> 53:08.648
Virginia: Well, then,
we'll just have to charm them.

53:21.863 --> 53:24.364
[ Clacking resumes ]

54:03.703 --> 54:06.004
[ Door opens ]

54:11.844 --> 54:15.213
Radio announcer: <i>...a 20-kiloton</i>
<i>blast over Niagara Falls,</i>

54:15.248 --> 54:17.482
<i>a 2-megaton blast over Seattle,</i>

54:17.516 --> 54:19.851
<i>and a single-megaton blast</i>
<i>over Detroit</i>

54:19.885 --> 54:22.921
<i>in this grim rehearsal</i>
<i>for disaster.</i>

54:22.956 --> 54:24.156
<i>Early estimates suggest</i>

54:24.190 --> 54:26.324
<i>more than half</i>
<i>the country's population</i>

54:26.358 --> 54:29.260
<i>would have been killed or</i>
<i>injured in the day's attacks,</i>

54:29.294 --> 54:32.129
<i>with clouds of radioactivity</i>
<i>rendering parts of the country</i>

54:32.164 --> 54:35.500
<i>uninhabitable</i>
<i>for years to come.</i>

54:35.534 --> 54:42.706
<i>In New York City alone, the</i>
<i>death toll stands at 2,339,000.</i>

54:42.740 --> 54:44.475
<i>The all-clears have sounded,</i>

54:44.509 --> 54:47.811
<i>but all is not well in America</i>
<i>tonight.</i>

54:47.846 --> 54:52.416
<i>Our sole consolation--</i>
<i>it was only a test.</i>

